<DOC><DOCNO> AP890608-0157 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-89 2051EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-China-RedCross     06-08 0256</FIRST><SECOND>AM-China-Red Cross,0262</SECOND><HEAD>Red Cross Estimates 3,600 Died In Beijing Crackdown</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chinese Red Cross officials estimate3,600 people were killed in the military assault on pro-democracydemonstrators in Beijing, a Chinese students' organization saidThursday.   The Union of Chinese Students in the Federal Republic also urgedthe West German government to impose sanctions on China for theweekend killings.   Hu Bo, a university student in Munich, said the union found outthrough communications with friends in China that the Chinese RedCross estimates 3,600 people died and 60,000 were injured whensoldiers routed protesters from Tiananmen Square.   The Chinese government says nearly 300 people, mostly soldiers,were killed. Chinese and foreign diplomats say up to 3,000 died.   At a news conference in Bonn, the union presented a young man whothe students said was a witness to the bloodshed in Beijing and hadjust returned to West Germany.   The Chinese man, who said he works for a company in West Germany,said army troops in Beijing shot indiscriminately at civilians andtheir homes.   ``I still have not recovered from this. It disturbs me verymuch,'' said the man, who would not give his name for fear ofpossible retaliation against his relatives.   ``A nurse I know went looking for her husband at a hospital.Bodies there were stacked one on top of the other,'' said the man.   The man said hospital officials told his nurse friend, ``How canwe look for him? There are so many bodies.''</TEXT></DOC>